  <h2><a href="../../blog-posts/china-looks-bus-rapid-transit-systems-cope-rapid-urbanization" title="China Looks to Bus Rapid Transit Systems to Cope with Rapid Urbanization">China Looks to Bus Rapid Transit Systems to Cope with Rapid Urbanization</a></h2>

      <span class="submitted">Posted by Nick Price on Feb 25, 2011</span>
  
  <div class="content clear-block">
    <div class="field field-type-filefield field-field-image">
    <div class="field-items">
            <div class="field-item odd">
                    <img src="../../files/chinainfo/imagecache/news-image/brt_blog_1.JPG" alt="" title="" width="178" height="120" class="imagecache imagecache-news-image imagecache-default imagecache-news-image_default"/>        </div>
        </div>
</div>
<p>Faced with a rapidly urbanizing population, China‚Äôs central government has set out to boost mass transit use in its largest cities to <a href="../../library/chinafaqs-chinas-transportation-revolution">60% from the current 35%</a>.  Yet with forecasts of up to <a href="http://www.mckinsey.com/mgi/publications/china_urban_summary_of_findings.asp">250 million cars on its roadways by 2025</a>, China must seek innovative ways to tackle that goal.  The recent success of the southern city of Guangzhou‚Äôs bus rapid transit system may provide part of the answer.</p>
  </div>
<div class="clear-block">
    	<div class="readmore"> <a href="../../blog-posts/china-looks-bus-rapid-transit-systems-cope-rapid-urbanization">Read more</a> </div>
