  <h2><a href="../../blog-posts/china-institutes-new-car-policies-are-they-enough" title="China Institutes New Car Policies, But Are They Enough?">China Institutes New Car Policies, But Are They Enough?</a></h2>

      <span class="submitted">Posted by Angel Hsu on Feb 18, 2011</span>
  
  <div class="content clear-block">
    <div class="field field-type-filefield field-field-image">
    <div class="field-items">
            <div class="field-item odd">
                    <img src="../../files/chinainfo/imagecache/news-image/beijing-hutong-car.jpg" alt="" title="" width="175" height="120" class="imagecache imagecache-news-image imagecache-default imagecache-news-image_default"/>        </div>
        </div>
</div>
<p>One present Santa may have brought a lot of Chinese families this year: a small car.  On [December 28th], the Chinese government announced a 10 percent sales tax on small cars effective January 1, sending many who had planned to purchase private vehicles in a dash to meet the year-end deadline.</p>
